    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some shipping docs for a run from Ningbo to Rotterdam. Can you explain the main differences between CIF and FOB under Incoterms 2020? Specifically, I need to know when the risk of loss actually transfers to us as the buyer.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main difference between CIF and FOB under Incoterms 2020 is where the seller's responsibility ends and the buyer's begins, particularly regarding risk transfer. With FOB (Free On Board), the risk transfers to the buyer when the goods are loaded onto the vessel at the port of origin (Ningbo). In contrast, CIF (Cost, Insurance, and Freight) requires the seller to cover the costs and insurance up to the destination port (Rotterdam), meaning the risk generally transfers to the buyer when the goods are loaded onto the vessel at the port of origin, similar to FOB.",
      "source": "target",
